"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444583","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-25","<p>The responses to the Government's Call for Evidence on the National Lottery, society lotteries and competing gambling products in raising funds for good causes will be published, excepting those that are commercially sensitive, in due course.</p><p>The Gambling Commission is also providing advice to Government on society lotteries in response to the CMS Select Committee report and we understand they will make this public in due course.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","22438","2016-01-25T13:53:04.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444583/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444583/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-13","National Lottery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to publish the recommendations of the Gambling Commission in response to his Department's call for evidence on the National Lottery and raising funds for good causes, launched in December 2014.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","22437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444584","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-25","<p>The responses to the Government's Call for Evidence on the National Lottery, society lotteries and competing gambling products in raising funds for good causes will be published, excepting those that are commercially sensitive, in due course.</p><p>The Gambling Commission is also providing advice to Government on society lotteries in response to the CMS Select Committee report and we understand they will make this public in due course.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","22437","2016-01-25T13:53:05.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444584/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444584/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-13","National Lottery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he intends to publish the responses to his Department's call for evidence on the National Lottery and raising funds for good causes, launched in December 2014.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","22438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444585","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>Thanks to an excellent Spending Review settlement in November 2015 - the Government is honouring its manifesto commitment to keep entry to the permanent collections of our national museums free.</p><br /><p>Through the Arts Council England, DCMS is increasing funding for major partner museums to £22.6 million to enable greater regional spending. In addition to this, regional museums can bid for funds from ACE's £10 million per year Resilience Fund. We are also investing millions of pounds to boost local and regional museums - for example, £5 million towards a new South Asia Gallery at Manchester Museum and £2.5 million to the Manchester Museum of Science andIndustry.</p><br /><p>Spend on DCMS-sponsored museums and galleries was £389.7 million in 2014/15. In 2005 spend was £397.4 million and in 2010 it was £474.7 million. The Heritage Lottery Fund is also a major source of support to museums. To date, HLF has supported a total of 38,000 projects with £6.6 billion across the UK with around one third of this being allocated to museums, including support for capital projects, acquisitions and skills development.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","22254 ; 22256","2016-01-29T13:32:49.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444585/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444585/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-13","Museums and Galleries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of how many museums and galleries charged for entry in (a) 2005 and (b) 2010; and what estimate his Department has made of how many museums and galleries plan to introduce such charges in 2016.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","22226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444586","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>Thanks to an excellent Spending Review settlement in November 2015 - the Government is honouring its manifesto commitment to keep entry to the permanent collections of our national museums free.</p><br /><p>Through the Arts Council England, DCMS is increasing funding for major partner museums to £22.6 million to enable greater regional spending. In addition to this, regional museums can bid for funds from ACE's £10 million per year Resilience Fund. We are also investing millions of pounds to boost local and regional museums - for example, £5 million towards a new South Asia Gallery at Manchester Museum and £2.5 million to the Manchester Museum of Science andIndustry.</p><br /><p>Spend on DCMS-sponsored museums and galleries was £389.7 million in 2014/15. In 2005 spend was £397.4 million and in 2010 it was £474.7 million. The Heritage Lottery Fund is also a major source of support to museums. To date, HLF has supported a total of 38,000 projects with £6.6 billion across the UK with around one third of this being allocated to museums, including support for capital projects, acquisitions and skills development.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","22226 ; 22256","2016-01-29T13:32:49.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444586/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444586/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-13","Museums and Galleries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department spent on museums and galleries in (a) 2005, (b) 2010 and (c) 2014-15; and what estimate he has made of such spending in (i) 2015-16 and (ii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","22254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444587","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-19","<p>In February 2015 the Chancellor announced that the government would fund the Barbican in the City of London to consider the feasibility of a creating a new world class concert hall in London.</p><p>As part of the Spending Review, the Chancellor agreed to provide a further £5.5million over the next 18 months for more detail business case work, which fully explore the costs and benefits of options for this project.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-19T16:35:32.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444587/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444587/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-13","Concert Halls: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the need for a new concert hall in London.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","22255"
