"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444809","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-19","<p>The fiscal implications of policy changes were published by the government in July 2015 “Summer Budget 2015: policy costings” and November 2015 “Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015: policy costings. See links below:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf</a></p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480565/SRAS2015_policy_costings_amended_page_25.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480565/SRAS2015_policy_costings_amended_page_25.pdf</a></p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-19T10:16:43.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444809/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444809/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444809/answer/previousversion/39706","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the spending reduction in 2016-17 that will result from (a) the changes in universal credit work allowances and (b) other changes in universal credit taking effect in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","22477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444810","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-19","<p>The number of people on benefits is driven by a range of factors. Because of this, the Universal Credit programme measures progress by the successful achievement of its delivery plan, rather than numbers of claimants.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-19T10:13:35.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444810/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444810/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444810/answer/previousversion/39702","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the number of people in work who will be in receipt of universal credit in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","22487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444915","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-19","<p>Procurement Policy Note 03/14 sets out the scope, background and detailed guidance for the policy of using the procurement process to promote tax compliance:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-policy-note-0314-promoting-tax-compliance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-policy-note-0314-promoting-tax-compliance</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-19T13:26:58.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444915/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444915/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-13","Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that government procurement helps to increase tax receipts.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","903123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445662","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-19","<p>Improving access to banking services is central to the Government’s agenda. I am therefore delighted that the nine largest personal current account providers in the UK have been offering new basic bank accounts since January 2016.</p><br /><p>For the first time, truly fee-free basic bank accounts are available for anyone who doesn’t have an account, or can’t use their account due to financial difficulty.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-19T17:15:30.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445662/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445662/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-13","Bank Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps he has taken to widen access to basic bank accounts.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","903117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445663","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-19","<p>The FCA are operationally independent of Government. They are responsible for deciding how to carry out their functions, and for assessing the implication of their actions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-19T17:17:13.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445663/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445663/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-13","HSBC","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the Financial Conduct Authority's decision to end its review into HSBC.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","903115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445664","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-19","<p>The government has provided significant support to first time exporters, many of whom are Small and Medium Enterprises.</p><br /><p>A significant package was announced at Autumn Statement 2014, and funding for this initiative was continued at Spending Review 2015.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-19T15:17:49.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445664/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445664/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-13","Small Businesses: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take fiscal steps to support exports by SMEs.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","903114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445665","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-19","<p>Last year the Government and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) jointly launched the Financial Advice Market Review. The Review is exploring how the UK’s financial advice market is operating for consumers, and what more can be done to ensure they have the access they need to high-quality, affordable advice so they can make informed decisions with their hard earned money. The Review will report ahead of Budget 2016.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-19T17:11:04.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445665/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445665/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-13","Financial Services: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to widen access to financial advice.","false","Biography information for James Berry","Kingston and Surbiton","James Berry","903119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444100","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-18","<p>Statistics for prosecutions and convictions for 2015, including those for offences defined as human trafficking, are planned for publication in May 2016.</p><br /><p>Overall court proceedings data for offences defined as human trafficking in England and Wales from 2004 to 2014 are published here.</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014</a></p><br /><p>The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority cannot provide data on the compensation it has awarded to victims of a particular crime type. This is because it awards compensation in line with the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme tariff of injuries rather than the type of incident that led to those injuries.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-18T09:21:00.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444100/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444100/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-12","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prosecutions for human trafficking resulted in a conviction between 1 August 2015 and 1 January 2016; and how many orders made for victim compensation as a result of such convictions resulted in payments (a) by convicted traffickers and (b) at a cost to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Mark Field","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","22061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444101","Attorney General","false","2016-01-20","<p>The Attorney General and I have not had any discussions on Pastor McConnell’s case with the Attorney General for Northern Ireland or the Public Prosecution Service. The decision to prosecute was a matter for the Public Prosecution Service.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-01-20T10:52:37.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444101/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444101/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-01-12","James McConnell","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether he has had discussions with his Northern Ireland counterparts on the recent case of Pastor James McConnell.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","22123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444102","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-20","<p><strong></strong></p><p>The Department does not hold the information required. However, BACS data shows that small and medium businesses are owed a total of £26.8 billion, and the average small business is waiting for £31,900 in overdue payments.[1]</p><br /><p>The Government recognises that late payment remains an important issue for small businesses in the UK and is taking significant steps to assist small businesses to recover late payment debts. This is part of a package of measures to tackle late payment. We have also legislated for new transparency measures in the public and private sectors.</p><br /><p>The Small Business Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 legislated for new reporting requirement on the UK’s largest companies and Regulations will be introduced this year which will compel larger companies to report on payment practices and performance. This information will be published on a six-monthly basis and will be made publicly available.</p><br /><p>The Public Contracts Regulations 2015 introduced a requirement for all public-sector buyers to publish annually, from 2017, their liability to debt interest payments. In central government we have gone further and faster. We will be publishing against these requirements quarterly from April this year. This will allow full public scrutiny of payment performance.</p><br /><p>Through the Enterprise Bill, currently before Parliament, we will legislate to establish a Small Business Commissioner to give general advice and to help small businesses resolve disputes relating to payment matters with larger businesses.</p><br /><p>Tackling late payment is about creating a responsible payment culture where larger companies recognise the benefit of having a sustainable and robust supply chain, and smaller businesses feel able to challenge poor behaviour. Once implemented, the Government is confident that these measures will lead to significant changes in the UK’s payment culture.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>[1] BACS Data June 2015.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","22125 ; 22126 ; 22130 ; 22183","2016-01-20T17:48:40.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444102/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444102/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-12","Small Businesses: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which 10 companies owed the greatest amount of late payment debt to SMEs in each six-month period of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","22124"
